---

### `how-it-works.html` — Process Explainer

**Section 1**: Hero. Eyebrow: `HOW IT WORKS`. H1: `From upload to audit, fully automated.` Subheading: `CMR DMS / DocAI is built around a repeating loop: organize, control, automate, monitor. Here is how it fits together.` [Manual §1 Quick Start]

**Section 2**: Vertical timeline — 6 numbered steps connected by a vertical teal line. [Manual §1, §3, §4, §5, §6, §7, §10, §11]

1. **Configure your foundation** [Manual §3, §4, §13]
   Set up your company branding (logo, banner, browser title). Define document categories and subcategories that mirror your org chart. Choose your storage backend (local or AWS S3 with encryption). Configure allowed file types and set your SMTP server for email notifications.

2. **Build your team and permissions** [Manual §4]
   Create user accounts and define roles with granular permission sets. Assign users to roles via drag-and-drop. Grant individual page-level permission overrides for edge cases. Add external clients to the client directory for reference alongside internal users.

3. **Upload and organize** [Manual §5, §6]
   Upload single files or batches. Set category, access visibility (Confidential / Public), and lifecycle status (Draft / Final / Archived). Add meta tags for searchability. Assign access to specific roles or users at upload time. Set expiration dates to prevent outdated documents from circulating.

4. **Collaborate, share, and finalize** [Manual §7, §6, §8, §10]
   Share documents with time-bounded access and optional download permissions. Generate password-protected external links. Add comments directly to documents for threaded, contextual discussion. Send documents by email, apply digital signatures, or add text watermarks — all from within the platform. Collect files from external parties via file request links. Set recurring reminders tied to documents or deadlines, delivered by email and in-app.

5. **Automate workflows and approvals** [Manual §11]
   Design multi-step approval workflows with named steps and transitions. Assign each step to the right user or role. Track progress in a visual graph — completed transitions in teal, pending ones in subdued tone. Receive notifications at every transition point. View all workflows organization-wide or filter to just yours.

6. **Monitor and comply** [Manual §14, §15]
   Review the full document audit trail — sortable and searchable by document, user, operation, or date. Monitor login audit logs for security visibility. Check email delivery logs and cron job execution logs for operational health. Apply archive retention policies to auto-delete documents after 30, 60, 90, 180, or 365 days.

**Section 3**: Video block — `assets/demo-workflow.mp4` styled as a dark monitor frame. Placeholder if missing. [Manual §11]

**Section 4**: Two-column comparison — **Before CMR DMS** vs **After CMR DMS** [Manual §2]

| Before | After |
|---|---|
| Documents scattered across emails and shared drives | Centralized, searchable library with category hierarchy |
| Manual email approval chains | Automated multi-step workflows with visual tracking |
| No version control — overwritten files | Complete version history with one-click restore |
| No record of who accessed or modified what | Full audit trail, searchable by document, user, and date |
| External file collection via email attachments | Controlled file request links with type and size limits |
| Compliance reporting done manually | Automated retention policies and exportable audit logs |

Render "Before" column in a dimmer palette with subtle red dash indicators. Render "After" column with teal checkmarks and full brightness.

